            background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
            border-radius: 4px;
        }

        .dropdown {
            position: absolute;
            top: 120%;
            left: 0;
            background-color: white;
            min-width: 200px;
            border-radius: 4px;
            box-shadow: 0 5px 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
            opacity: 0;
            visibility: hidden;
            transform: translateY(10px);
            transition: all 0.3s ease;
        }

        .nav-item:hover .dropdown {
            opacity: 1;
            visibility: visible;
            transform: translateY(0);
        }

        .dropdown-item {
            display: block;
            padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
            color: #2c3e50;
            text-decoration: none;
            transition: background-color 0.2s ease;
        }

        .dropdown-item:hover {
            background-color: #f5f5f5;
            color: #3498db;
        }

        .arrow {
            font-size: 0.8em;
            margin-left: 5px;
            transition: transform 0.3s ease;
        }

        .nav-item:hover .arrow {
            transform: rotate(180deg);
        }

        /* Responsive Design */
        @media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
            .nav-menu {
                flex-direction: column;
                align-items: center;
            }

            .nav-item {
                margin: 0.5rem 0;
            }

            .dropdown {
                position: static;
                display: none;
                opacity: 1;
                visibility: visible;
                transform: none;
                background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
                box-shadow: none;
            }

            .dropdown.active {
                display: block;
            }

            .dropdown-item {
                color: white;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <nav class="navbar">
        <ul class="nav-menu">
            <li class="nav-item">
                <a href="#" class="nav-link">Home</a>
            </li>
            <li class="nav-item">
                <a href="#" class="nav-link">Products <span class="arrow">▼</span></a>
                <div class="dropdown">
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Electronics</a>
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Clothing</a>
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Books</a>
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Home Decor</a>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li class="nav-item">
                <a href="#" class="nav-link">Services <span class="arrow">▼</span></a>
                <div class="dropdown">
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Consulting</a>
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Support</a>
                    <a href="#" class="dropdown-item">Training</a>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li class="nav-item">
                <a href="#" class="nav-link">About</a>
            </li>
            <li class="nav-item">
                <a href="#" class="nav-link">Contact</a>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </nav>

    <script>
        // Toggle dropdown on mobile view
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            const navItems = document.querySelectorAll('.nav-item');

            navItems.forEach(item => {
                const link = item.querySelector('.nav-link');
                const dropdown = item.querySelector('.dropdown');

                if (dropdown) {
                    link.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
                        if (window.innerWidth <= 768) {
                            e.preventDefault();
                            dropdown.classList.toggle('active');
                        }
                    });
                }
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Code

#### **HTML Structure**
- The navigation menu is built using a `<nav>` element with an unordered list (`<ul>`) for the main menu items.
- Dropdown menus are implemented as `<div>` elements with the class `dropdown` inside each relevant `<li>` (nav-item).
- Each dropdown contains links with the class `dropdown-item`.

#### **CSS Styling**
- **Navbar**: Fixed at the top with a dark background (`#2c3e50`), subtle shadow, and full-width layout.
- **Navigation Items**: Displayed flexibly with centered alignment, white text, and hover effects (color change to `#3498db` and slight background opacity).
- **Dropdown**: Hidden by default with `opacity: 0` and `visibility: hidden`. On hover, it appears with a smooth transition (opacity, transform, and visibility changes). It has a white background, subtle shadow, and rounded corners.
- **Hover Effects**: Smooth color transitions for links and background changes for dropdown items.
- **Arrow Animation**: A small downward arrow rotates 180 degrees on hover using `transform`.
- **Responsive Design**: On screens smaller than 768px, the menu stacks vertically, and dropdowns are toggled by click instead of hover (handled by JS). Dropdowns are styled differently for mobile to blend with the navbar.

#### **JavaScript Functionality**
- A simple script handles mobile responsiveness. On smaller screens, clicking a menu item with a dropdown toggles its visibility by adding/removing the `active` class.
- The script uses `window.innerWidth` to determine if the device is in mobile view (≤768px).

#### **Design Features**
- **Modern Look**: Clean color scheme (dark navbar with blue accents), subtle shadows, and rounded corners.
- **Interactive**: Smooth transitions for hover effects and dropdown animations (0.3s ease).
- **Responsive**: Adapts to mobile view with a vertical menu and click-to-toggle dropdowns.
- **Accessibility**: Clear contrast between text and background, and semantic HTML structure.

### How to Use
1. Copy the entire code into a `.html` file (e.g., `nav-menu.html`).
2. Open it in a browser to see the interactive menu.
3. Test the hover effects on desktop and click-to-toggle dropdowns on mobile view (resize the browser or use developer tools to simulate mobile).

This navigation menu is ready to use and can be customized by changing colors, fonts, or spacing in the CSS, or by adding more menu items and dropdowns in the HTML.

ere's a complete implementation of a custom range slider for audio volume control in a single file using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. The design is modern and interactive, with a smooth gradient thumb, hover effects, and a dynamic progress bar that reflects the volume level.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Custom Audio Volume Slider</title>
    <style>
        * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }

        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            min-height: 100vh;
            background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1a1a2e 0%, #16213e 100%);
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
        }

        .volume-control {
            background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
            backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
            border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
            border-radius: 16px;
            padding: 20px;
            width: 300px;
            text-align: center;
            box-shadow: 0 8px 32px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }

        .volume-control h3 {
            color: white;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
            font-size: 1.2rem;
            text-transform: uppercase;
            letter-spacing: 1px;
        }

        .slider-container {
            position: relative;
            width: 100%;
            height: 10px;
            background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        .slider-progress {
            position: absolute;
            height: 100%;
            width: 50%;
            background: linear-gradient(to right, #00b09b, #96c93d);
            border-radius: 5px;
            pointer-events: none;
        }

        input[type="range"] {
            -webkit-appearance: none;
            width: 100%;
            height: 10px;
            background: transparent;
            cursor: pointer;
            position: relative;
            z-index: 2;
        }

        input[type="range"]::-webkit-slider-thumb {
            -webkit-appearance: none;
            width: 20px;
            height: 20px;
            background: linear-gradient(to bottom right, #00b09b, #96c93d);
            border-radius: 50%;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: transform 0.2s ease;
            position: relative;
            z-index: 3;
            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
        }

        input[type="range"]::-webkit-slider-thumb:hover {
            transform: scale(1.1);
        }

        input[type="range"]::-webkit-slider-thumb:active {
            transform: scale(0.9);
        }

        .volume-value {
            color: white;
            margin-top: 10px;
            font-size: 1.1rem;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        .volume-icon {
            color: white;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            font-size: 1.5rem;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="volume-control">
        <h3>Volume Control</h3>
        <div class="volume-icon" id="volumeIcon">🔊</div>
        <div class="slider-container">
            <div class="slider-progress" id="sliderProgress"></div>
            <input type="range" id="volumeSlider" min="0" max="100" value="50">
        </div>
        <div class="volume-value" id="volumeValue">50%</div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const volumeSlider = document.getElementById('volumeSlider');
        const sliderProgress = document.getElementById('sliderProgress');
        const volumeValue = document.getElementById('volumeValue');
        const volumeIcon = document.getElementById('volumeIcon');

        function updateSlider() {
            const value = volumeSlider.value;
            // Update progress bar width
            sliderProgress.style.width = `${value}%`;
            // Update volume percentage text
            volumeValue.textContent = `${value}%`;
            // Update volume icon based on value
            if (value === '0') {
                volumeIcon.textContent = '🔇';
            } else if (value < 50) {
                volumeIcon.textContent = '🔉';
            } else {
                volumeIcon.textContent = '🔊';
            }
        }

        // Update slider on input change
        volumeSlider.addEventListener('input', updateSlider);

        // Update slider when clicking on the slider container (progress bar)
        document.querySelector('.slider-container').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
            const rect = e.currentTarget.getBoundingClientRect();
            const clickX = e.clientX - rect.left;
            const width = rect.width;
            const newValue = Math.round((clickX / width) * 100);
            volumeSlider.value = newValue;
            updateSlider();
        });

        // Simulate audio volume control (you can connect this to an actual audio element)
        volumeSlider.addEventListener('input', () => {
            const audio = document.querySelector('audio'); // Example: Connect to an audio element if exists
            if (audio) {
                audio.volume = volumeSlider.value / 100;
            }
        });

        // Initialize slider on load
        updateSlider();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Design and Features:

#### **HTML Structure**
- A container `volume-control` holds the entire slider UI.
- Inside, there's a title, a volume icon, a slider container with a progress bar, the actual range input, and a volume percentage display.

#### **CSS Styling**
- **Background and Container**: The page uses a dark gradient background with a glassy card effect for the volume control container using `backdrop-filter: blur`.
- **Slider Design**: The slider track is styled as a thin bar with a semi-transparent background. The progress bar uses a vibrant gradient for visual appeal.
- **Thumb Styling**: The slider thumb is a circular element with a gradient fill, hover scaling, and press effects for interactivity.
- **Responsive and Clean**: The design is centered, minimal, and uses modern effects like shadows and gradients for a polished look.

#### **JavaScript Functionality**
- **Slider Update**: The `updateSlider` function dynamically updates the progress bar width and volume percentage text as the slider value changes.
- **Icon Feedback**: The volume icon changes dynamically based on the volume level (mute, low, high).
- **Click Interaction**: Clicking anywhere on the slider container adjusts the volume to the clicked position, calculated as a percentage of the slider width.
- **Audio Integration**: The script includes a placeholder to control an audio element's volume (commented out, can be connected to a real `<audio>` tag if needed).

#### **Interactive Features**
- Hover and click animations on the slider thumb.
- Clicking on the slider track directly updates the volume.
- Visual feedback through the progress bar and changing icons.
- Smooth transitions for a premium feel.

To use this with actual audio, simply add an `<audio>` tag to the HTML and uncomment the relevant JS code to link the slider value to the audio volume. This design is mobile-friendly and can be further customized by adjusting colors, sizes, or icons to match your project's theme.

