            padding: 0 25px;
            max-height: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
            background: #ffffff;
            transition: max-height 0.3s cubic-bezier(0, 1, 0, 1);
        }

        .accordion-content p {
            padding: 20px 0;
            line-height: 1.6;
            color: #555;
            font-size: 16px;
        }

        .accordion-item.active .accordion-content {
            max-height: 300px; /* Adjust based on content */
            transition: max-height 0.3s cubic-bezier(0.5, 0, 1, 0);
        }

        .accordion-item.active .accordion-header span {
            transform: rotate(-180deg);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="accordion">
        <div class="accordion-item">
            <div class="accordion-header">
                <h3>What is an Accordion Menu?</h3>
                <span>▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-content">
                <p>An accordion menu is a vertically stacked list of headers that can be clicked to reveal or hide content associated with them. It's commonly used to save space on a webpage while providing access to multiple sections of content.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
            <div class="accordion-header">
                <h3>How Does It Work?</h3>
                <span>▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-content">
                <p>Clicking on a header toggles the visibility of its content. CSS transitions create a smooth animation effect, while JavaScript handles the toggling logic. Only one section can be open at a time in this implementation.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="accordion-item">
            <div class="accordion-header">
                <h3>Benefits of Using Accordions</h3>
                <span>▼</span>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-content">
                <p>Accordions help organize content in a compact way, improve user experience by reducing clutter, and make navigation easier on both desktop and mobile devices. They're perfect for FAQs, menus, and detailed information.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            const accordionItems = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-item');

            accordionItems.forEach(item => {
                const header = item.querySelector('.accordion-header');
                const content = item.querySelector('.accordion-content');

                header.addEventListener('click', () => {
                    // Close all other items
                    accordionItems.forEach(otherItem => {
                        if (otherItem !== item && otherItem.classList.contains('active')) {
                            otherItem.classList.remove('active');
                            otherItem.querySelector('.accordion-content').style.maxHeight = 0;
                        }
                    });

                    // Toggle current item
                    item.classList.toggle('active');
                    if (item.classList.contains('active')) {
                        content.style.maxHeight = content.scrollHeight + 'px';
                    } else {
                        content.style.maxHeight = 0;
                    }
                });
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of the Implementation:

#### **HTML Structure**
- The accordion is wrapped in a `div` with the class `accordion`.
- Each section is an `accordion-item` containing an `accordion-header` (clickable trigger) and `accordion-content` (expandable content).
- The header includes a title (`h3`) and an arrow icon (`span`) for visual feedback.
- Content is hidden by default and expands when the header is clicked.

#### **CSS Design**
- **Styling**: Uses a clean, modern design with a white card-like container, subtle shadows, and a gradient background for the page.
- **Transitions**: Smooth expansion/collapse is achieved using `max-height` with CSS transitions. The `cubic-bezier` timing functions create a natural animation feel (fast start for closing, slow start for opening).
- **Hover Effects**: Headers change background color on hover for interactivity.
- **Arrow Animation**: The arrow rotates 180 degrees when a section is active using `transform: rotate()`.
- **Responsive**: The accordion is centered and has a max-width for better readability on larger screens.

#### **JavaScript Functionality**
- **Event Listener**: Waits for the DOM to load before attaching click events to each accordion header.
- **Toggle Logic**: When a header is clicked, it closes all other open sections (if any) and toggles the clicked section's `active` class.
- **Dynamic Height**: Sets the `max-height` of the content dynamically based on its `scrollHeight` for a smooth transition. Resets to `0` when collapsing.
- **Single Open**: Only one accordion item can be open at a time for better usability (can be modified to allow multiple open sections if needed).

#### **Features**
- **Smooth Animation**: Uses CSS transitions for a fluid expand/collapse effect.
- **Interactive Design**: Hover states and rotating arrows provide visual feedback.
- **Accessibility**: Headers are clickable and structured with semantic HTML for better screen reader support.
- **Modern Look**: Gradient background, shadows, and clean typography create a professional appearance.

#### **How to Use**
1. Save this code in a `.html` file (e.g., `accordion.html`).
2. Open it in a web browser to see the accordion in action.
3. Click on any header to expand/collapse its content. Only one section opens at a time.

#### **Customization Options**
- Adjust the `max-height` value in CSS (or JS `scrollHeight`) if your content is taller/shorter.
- Change colors, fonts, and spacing in the CSS to match your design theme.
- Modify the JS to allow multiple sections to be open by removing the loop that closes other items.
- Add icons or images to headers/content for richer visuals.

