I'll create a single-file weather widget using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript that fetches real-time weather data from the OpenWeatherMap API. The design will be modern and responsive with interactive elements, including a search feature for different cities.

To use this widget, you'll need to sign up for a free API key at https://openweathermap.org/api. Once you have the key, replace `'YOUR_API_KEY'` in the JavaScript code with your actual key.

Here's the complete code with comments for clarity:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Weather Widget</title>
    <style>
        * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            box-sizing: border-box;
            font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
        }

        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            min-height: 100vh;
            background: linear-gradient(135deg, #6ab1e7, #4f42b5);
        }

        .weather-widget {
            background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.9);
            border-radius: 20px;
            padding: 30px;
            width: 100%;
            max-width: 400px;
            box-shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
            backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
            transition: transform 0.3s ease;
        }

        .weather-widget:hover {
            transform: translateY(-5px);
        }

        .search-container {
            display: flex;
            gap: 10px;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }

        #cityInput {
            flex: 1;
            padding: 12px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            outline: none;
            transition: border-color 0.3s ease;
        }

        #cityInput:focus {
            border-color: #4f42b5;
        }

        #searchBtn {
            padding: 12px 20px;
            border: none;
            background: #4f42b5;
            color: white;
            border-radius: 10px;
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 16px;
            transition: background 0.3s ease;
        }

        #searchBtn:hover {
            background: #3a2d8c;
        }

        .weather-info {
            text-align: center;
        }

        .city-name {
            font-size: 28px;
            font-weight: 600;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            color: #333;
        }

        .weather-icon {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            margin: 0 auto;
        }

        .temperature {
            font-size: 48px;
            font-weight: 700;
            color: #333;
            margin: 10px 0;
        }

        .weather-description {
            font-size: 18px;
            color: #666;
            text-transform: capitalize;
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }

        .details {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
            gap: 15px;
            text-align: left;
        }

        .detail-item {
            background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.8);
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }

        .detail-item span {
            display: block;
            font-size: 14px;
            color: #666;
        }

        .detail-item p {
            font-size: 18px;
            font-weight: 600;
            color: #333;
        }

        .loading, .error {
            text-align: center;
            font-size: 18px;
            color: #666;
            display: none;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="weather-widget">
        <div class="search-container">
            <input type="text" id="cityInput" placeholder="Enter city name...">
            <button id="searchBtn">Search</button>
        </div>
        <div class="weather-info" id="weatherInfo" style="display: none;">
            <h2 class="city-name" id="cityName"></h2>
            <img class="weather-icon" id="weatherIcon" src="" alt="Weather Icon">
            <div class="temperature" id="temperature"></div>
            <div class="weather-description" id="weatherDescription"></div>
            <div class="details">
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <span>Humidity</span>
                    <p id="humidity"></p>
                </div>
                <div class="detail-item">
                    <span>Wind Speed</span>
                    <p id="windSpeed"></p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="loading" id="loading">Loading weather data...</div>
        <div class="error" id="error">Unable to fetch weather data. Please try again.</div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const apiKey = 'YOUR_API_KEY'; // Replace with your OpenWeatherMap API key
        const weatherInfo = document.getElementById('weatherInfo');
        const loading = document.getElementById('loading');
        const error = document.getElementById('error');
        const cityInput = document.getElementById('cityInput');
        const searchBtn = document.getElementById('searchBtn');

        // Function to fetch weather data
        async function fetchWeather(city) {
            try {
                loading.style.display = 'block';
                weatherInfo.style.display = 'none';
                error.style.display = 'none';

                const response = await fetch(
                    `https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?q=${city}&appid=${apiKey}&units=metric`
                );

                if (!response.ok) {
                    throw new Error('City not found');
                }

                const data = await response.json();
                displayWeather(data);
            } catch (err) {
                loading.style.display = 'none';
                error.style.display = 'block';
            }
        }

        // Function to display weather data
        function displayWeather(data) {
            loading.style.display = 'none';
            weatherInfo.style.display = 'block';

            document.getElementById('cityName').textContent = data.name;
            document.getElementById('temperature').textContent = `${Math.round(data.main.temp)}°C`;
            document.getElementById('weatherDescription').textContent = data.weather[0].description;
            document.getElementById('humidity').textContent = `${data.main.humidity}%`;
            document.getElementById('windSpeed').textContent = `${data.wind.speed} m/s`;
            document.getElementById('weatherIcon').src = 
                `https://openweathermap.org/img/wn/${data.weather[0].icon}@2x.png`;
        }

        // Event listener for search button
        searchBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const city = cityInput.value.trim();
            if (city) {
                fetchWeather(city);
            }
        });

        // Event listener for Enter key
        cityInput.addEventListener('keypress', (e) => {
            if (e.key === 'Enter') {
                const city = cityInput.value.trim();
                if (city) {
                    fetchWeather(city);
                }
            }
        });

        // Default city on load
        fetchWeather('London');
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Features and Design Choices:
1. **API Integration**: Uses the OpenWeatherMap API to fetch real-time weather data. You need to replace `'YOUR_API_KEY'` with your actual API key.
2. **Responsive Design**: The widget is centered on the page, has a max-width for larger screens, and uses flexible units for responsiveness.
3. **Modern Styling**: 
   - Glassmorphism effect with a semi-transparent background and blur.
   - Gradient background for the body.
   - Smooth hover effects on the widget and button.
   - Clean typography and spacing.
4. **Interactive Elements**:
   - Search input with a button and Enter key support to fetch weather for any city.
   - Hover animation on the widget for a subtle lift effect.
5. **Error Handling**: Displays loading and error states if the API call fails or the city is not found.
6. **Data Display**: Shows city name, temperature, weather description, humidity, wind speed, and a weather icon from the API.
7. **Default Behavior**: Loads weather data for London on page load as a default.

### How to Use:
1. Save this code in a file (e.g., `weather-widget.html`).
2. Replace `'YOUR_API_KEY'` in the JavaScript section with your OpenWeatherMap API key.
3. Open the file in a web browser. You'll see the weather for London by default.
4. Enter any city name in the search input and click "Search" or press Enter to get updated weather data.

